for 2010 and 2009, other postretirement benefits paid are net of $15 million and $28 million of medicare subsidy receipts, respectively.
for u.s. plans, the discount rate is determined by constructing a portfolio of high-quality, noncallable bonds with cash
flows that match estimated outflows for benefit payments. for major non-u.s. plans, the discount rate is determined by using bond portfolios with an average maturity approximating that of the liabilities or spot yield curves, both of which are
constructed using high-quality, local-currency-denominated bonds.  the measurement of the accumulated postretirement benefit
obligation assumes an initial health care cost trend rate of 6.0 percent that declines to 4.5 percent by 2015. a one-percentage-point increase in the health care cost trend rate would increase service and interest cost by $57 million and the
postretirement benefit obligation by $599 million. a one-percentage-point decrease in the health care cost trend rate would decrease service and interest cost by $45 million and the post-retirement benefit obligation by $494 million.
